  m_Script: {fileID: 11500000, guid: dc6f926697812614b85702b2e9982a93, type: 3}
  m_Name: NamingConvention
  m_EditorClassIdentifier: Documentation::NamingConvention
  conventionText: '<b><size=16>Prefab Naming</size></b>


    This naming convention
    serves as a practical middle ground between Unity and Unreal Engine conventions.
    The prefixes act as quick visual hints to help team members and developers instantly
    understand what type of prefab they''re working with, without needing to open
    it first.


    <b><size=14>Prefix Guide</size></b>


    <b>P_</b> - Standard
    Prefab

    A basic prefab containing any general game object or component setup.


    <b>P_V_</b>
    - Prefab Variant

    A variant of an existing prefab with modified properties
    or components.


    <b>PA_</b> - Prefab Actor

    A prefab representing an
    interactive game entity or character (borrowed from Unreal''s "Actor" concept).


    <b>PAV_</b>
    - Prefab Actor Variant

    A variant of an Actor prefab with customized settings.


    <b>PP_</b>
    - Prefab Pawn

    A prefab for controllable characters or entities (using Unreal''s
    "Pawn" terminology for player-controllable objects).


    <b>PAI_</b> - Prefab
    AI-Controlled Pawn

    A prefab specifically for AI-controlled characters, making
    it clear this entity uses autonomous behavior.


    <b>PUI_</b> - Prefab UI

    A
    prefab containing user interface elements.


    <b><size=16>UI Element Suffixes</size></b>


    UI
    elements within prefabs use descriptive suffixes to identify their function and
    type at a glance. These suffixes are appended to the end of GameObject names
    within UI prefabs.


    <b>_CNT</b> - Container

    An empty container object
    used for layout and organization, similar to a <div> in HTML. Typically holds
    other UI elements and helps structure the interface hierarchy.

    Example:
    MainMenu_CNT, InventoryPanel_CNT


    <b>_BTN</b> - Button

    A button object
    that handles user input and interactions. Usually contains a Button component
    along with visual elements and text.

    Example: StartGame_BTN, CloseWindow_BTN


    <b>_BG</b>
    - Background

    A background object that provides visual backing for UI panels,
    windows, or other elements. Often contains an Image component for rendering sprites
    or solid colors.

    Example: Panel_BG, Window_BG


    <b>_TXT</b> - Text

    A
    text display object, usually a TextMeshPro component. Used for labels, titles,
    descriptions, and any other text content in the UI.

    Example: PlayerName_TXT,
    ScoreLabel_TXT


    <b>_IMG</b> - Image

    A pure visual element containing
    only an image component without interactive logic. Used for icons, decorative
    elements, sprites, and other graphical content that doesn''t require user interaction.

    Example:
    PlayerAvatar_IMG, ItemIcon_IMG, Decoration_IMG


    <i>Note: These prefixes
    and suffixes are organizational tools to improve workflow efficiency. They give
    you an at-a-glance understanding of a prefab''s purpose and contents, saving
    time during development and collaboration. When combined, they create clear,
    self-documenting names like ''PUI_InventoryWindow'' containing objects such as
    ''Header_CNT'', ''CloseButton_BTN'', ''Background_BG'', and ''Title_TXT''.</i>'
